        <p><img src="/assets/icons/bench.svg" alt="Bench icon by Mega Agustina (The Noun Project)"
                style="display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;" width="40px" class="filter"></p>
        <p>"How can the end of the world look so beautiful?" A voice, angelic sounding, between all the rumbles around
            me that signifies the end as we know it, shattered my silence and peace.</p>
        <p>I opened my eyes. I have been meditating on a bench in a park near my apartment. I slowly acquainted myself
            with the colors as my retina received them. The light grew ever slightly as the countdown to the inescapable
            blast began. I turned my head to the sky and watched the moon fall towards Earth at an incredible speed. The
            moon began its descent towards Earth after a mining colony incident resulted in an explosion. The explosion
            was grand enough that it began to shatter the moon. That was only the beginning of the end.</p>
        <p>"Hey," the voice says, interrupting my drastically depressing self-exposition. "What do you think?"</p>
        <p>"What do I think about what?" I replied.</p>
        <p>"The skies. How can it look so beautiful even though it's supposed to destroy us?" She said.</p>
        <p>"Beauty exists both in creation and destruction."</p>
        <p>"That's the wisest thing you have said since we met," she said sarcastically. She must've thought it was
            sappy.</p>
        <p>"What can I say? The end of the world brings out the artistic side in me." I close my eyes again, trying to
            find the same peace I acquired before I was interrupted. But of course, I can't find it again.</p>
        <p>"Say, how about we do something-"</p>
        <p>"Damnit, we agreed not to talk for about 15 minutes. Why did you have to interrupt me?" I was annoyed.</p>
        <p>"Whoa, okay. Chill, dude. It's literally the end of the world. Why can't we talk for a second?"</p>
        <p>"I was trying to find peace."</p>
        <p>"Peace can be found within each other."</p>
        <p>I opened my eyes again and looked at her. "Now YOU'RE being sappy."</p>
        <p>She was a stranger, someone who found me in the first hour of my journey to find peace in this serene park.
            She was a young woman, brunette, probably in her mid-20s or late 20s, wearing stylish clothing that looked
            dirty, like it had been a while since it got washed. She also wore a backpack.</p>
        <p>We never discussed any names, nor did we speak about our personal information. We just talked about
            everything else. What games would we miss playing? What book series would we want to see written to the
            finish? What apocalyptic movies predicted the end of the world? When we ran out of topics to discuss, I
            proposed that we have a 15-minute silence so that I could find peace in meditation. She broke that in less
            than 5 minutes.</p>
        <p>She was looking at her feet, her eyes downcast and barely hiding the gloomy interior. She must've been
            anxious to spend time alone, a typical extrovert. I can't help but feel bad.</p>
        <p>"I'm sorry." I finally said after a few seconds. "It's just that sometimes I need some silence in my life.
            Especially after our long discussion before, it drains me."</p>
        <p>"Oh, okay. Sorry for interrupting your charging session." She said, eyes still looking downwards.</p>
        <p>"Nah, it's okay. I can't focus with this trembling ambiance anyway." I tried to lighten the mood. But after I
            said that, silence began to descend upon us. So I broke the ice by asking a question.</p>
        <p>"Where are you from anyway?" I began asking personal questions. I thought, hell, it's the end of the world
            anyway. What more do I have to lose?</p>
        <p>She said her answer, somewhere far from here. "I was here because I was visiting my boyfriend. We were in a
            long-distance relationship."</p>
        <p>Her trembling hands and almost teary eyes confirmed my suspicions about her being alone. With the world
            turning into disarray as the moon shattered, ugly things happened. I'm talking about animal attacks,
            poisonous gas, extreme heat or cold weather, and a superstorm. That was the bulk of what happened to the
            world, at least. My city only appeared to be attacked by a pack of spiders, big enough to compare to a dog.
            I survived because they didn't check through my building, which was unoccupied like the other buildings in
            this city. Most people either died already or died on their way to escape. My survival was only through the
            element of luck.</p>
        <p>I guess her boyfriend wasn't as lucky as I am. But none of this matters when the freaking moon is heading
            towards the world as we know it. Not even luck can save us from being vaporized by the impact of something
            of that size.</p>
        <p>"Aren't you sick of using pronouns to refer to me?" I said, lightening the topic. "How about we introduce
            ourselves, but it's completely up to us whether it's made up or not."</p>
        <p>Her face still showed an apparent sadness, but it brightened ever so slightly when she heard that idea. It
            seemed like she liked childish ideas like this. Well, that makes two of us. What do I have to lose?</p>
        <p><img src="/assets/icons/bench.svg" alt="Bench icon by Mega Agustina (The Noun Project)"
                style="display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;" width="40px" class="filter"></p>
        <p>"So let me get this straight," she said. "Your name is D*rth B*nks?"</p>
        <p>"Guilty as charged," I replied.</p>
        <p>She narrowed her eyes, then smirked. "Alright then, my name is Ani Skyw*lker."</p>
        <p>I gasped. "No, you did not."</p>
        <p>"I just did." She said with a smirk that grew wider by the minute. "So let's stop messing around and drop the
            made-up names?"</p>
        <p>"Alright, fine." I held my hand up, preparing for a customary handshake. "Name's Ben Parker."</p>
        <p>"You heard me before when I said we should stop messing around, right?"</p>
        <p>"I'm not joking, okay? My name is Ben, the full name's Ruben Parker, but I hate it when people call me Ruben,
            so I nicknamed myself Ben."</p>
        <p>"I assume you do that after-"</p>
        <p>"No. No, no. I was the target of multiple jokes because of that. It didn't help make me feel better about my
            choices." I voiced my frustration. It was one year ago, but I'll trade everything I had to experience those
            days instead of living in this current hell.</p>
        <p>She laughed at my attempt to justify my nickname choice and said, "Alright, Ben." She uttered the name
            mockingly. "My name is Tess, full name Theresa Pollock. Unlike you, I do not have to manufacture a new
            nickname because my name is versatile enough to be called anything." She took my outstretched hand and shook
            it.</p>
        <p>I smirked. "Sure, Miss Pollock."</p>
        <p>"That makes me sound old."</p>
        <p>"You are old, older than me, probably."</p>
        <p>Tess raised her eyebrows. "Oh? What makes you say that?"</p>
        <p>I dramatically checked her out and said, "Late 20s, I assume?" I didn't let Tess say another word before
            going forward with a mocking tone, like that famous detective with a funny hat. "Wrinkle in your cheeks,
            wrinkles in your hands, wrinkles everywhere. No way you're younger than me, and I know my age. A little bit
            of dust here shows me absolutely nothing 'cause I'm just pulling it out of my ass."</p>
        <p>We both laughed at my cringy attempt to emulate the master detective that is Sherlock Holmes.</p>
        <p>"I guess you love Sherlock, huh?"</p>
        <p>"Best character in the book format I've ever read. It shaped my childhood and reminded me of a memory." Tess
            said wistfully. "I think I also did that a long time ago, so it's fun being the one witnessing the attempt
            this time."</p>